\pard\plain \fi360\sl288\slmult1\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf4 Tricking is strange in that it has a relatively high barrier to entry however the retention rate is surprisingly high for those who do get into it. You either love tricking with a fiery passion or you couldn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t care less about it. It\u8217\'92s almost as if Tricking finds us and pulls us into it and holds us there until we find ourselves immersed in this underground world of real life ninjas and super humans.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf4  As we\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92ve seen by going through the terminology and technicals section, Tricking is rather complex. It has many things that are difficult to fully understand how they work together without taking the time to develop a deep understanding of the system. But once we start developing that understanding, exceptional worlds of possibility open up before us. We see areas that, while they have been mapped, have not been truly explored physically, first hand. All of the theory needs to be made real through our actions. There is so much that tricking has to offer once we get over that initial barrier of trying to figure out what it is, and start realizing what it can do.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf4 Sometimes the simplest starting rules can lead to emergent systems that appear to take on their own life. Take John Conway\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s Game of Life. This is a cellular automaton computer program that has only a few simple rules. It contains a grid of cells which abide by the following rules to control their state. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf4 1. Any live cell with one or no neighbors dies, as if by loneliness. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf4 2. Any live cell with four or more cells dies, as if by overpopulation. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf4 3. Any live cell with two or three neighbors survives. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf4 4. Any dead cell with three neighbors comes alive, as if born.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf4 Which can be simplified even further to three rules.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf4 1. Any live cell with two or three live neighbors survives.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf4 2. Any Dead cell with three live neighbors becomes a live cell.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf4 3. All others cells die, or stay dead in the next generation}
